<br>
----------------------------------<br>
<br>
Before I get started saying things that arent positive I want to publicly thank the devs for allowing me to test this game, they really are trying to make this game good, at this point I dont think Q is sleeping and I doubt many of the other devs are either judging by the list of things being worked on. <br>
This is probably going to be beta_tester_review#_13252 but I know that people are truely interested in what SWG is and isnt. <br>
<br>
It isnt EQ<br>
It Isnt DAOC<br>
It isnt UO<br>
It isnt AO<br>
It isnt planetside<br>
It isnt jedi knight II <br>
<br>
I played all those games some for a very long time. When I was less than pleased in beta I referred to SWG as &quot;sims in space&quot;. For everyone that moaned about SWG becoming EQ in space, after about 5 months of trying to play SWG as SWG and not another game I began to wish there was even a little truth to that, but theres not. <br>
<br>
What is it? I started beta in November and tested ever since and I still cant tell you what the game has succeeded in being. It has never been &quot;fun&quot;. Why did I continue to play? It was a beta, I agreed to test it for them and the game wasnt supposed to be fun until a month or two ago. After the devs officially gave us permission to have fun (really..they made a post about this  ) I started to look at why I hadnt been having fun and came to the determination that the core design of the game just didnt work for me. <br>
<br>
It is a very pretty game, walking through bestine truely feels like being in starwars. There are areas of some of the planets that are simply stunning. <br>
<br>
I can tell you one thing, I canceled my preorder. <br>
<br>
One observation that I (and others) made over and over in beta, if you ever liked playing EQ or DAOC (even if you eventually burned out), you will probably not enjoy SWG. <br>
If you dont like combat, if dancing the night away in a cantina is your thing, SWG might be your game. <br>
<br>
If you like crafting..well I'll let someone more experienced in the crafting system fill you in on that. The outsite looking in view is &quot;broken&quot; but dont quote me on that I tested combat primarily. <br>
<br>
I wont bitch about stability, bugs, travel times,subscription charges, or even PVP those things dont worry me, my issues are much more to the core of the game. Things that looked ok when I was looking at what I thought was the framework of a game last year that never really were fleshed to make them fun for me. Mechanics so core to the game that no company would dare change them significantly after releasing a game. <br>
SWG does not offer a compelling game for the one thing I want to do in online games: combat. I am not interested in crafting or playing the role of a cantina resident. <br>
<br>
The combat system has been flavored by the basic design goals of making it accessible for players with no MMORPG experience and reducing the difference between the effectiveness and survivability of new characters vs ones who have been played 40 hours a week for 6 months. <br>
<br>
The result of these design goals is a combat system on training wheels and nearly no tangible reward for advancement. Almost counter that in fact. The more you have advanced up the skill trees the worse you tend to find you fight versus a single NPC of similar &quot;con&quot; or consider value, much less more than one of them. <br>
<br>
Allow me to explain a bit more. <br>
<br>
Root cause #1 the HAM system: <br>
Essentially you have 3 bars health, action, and mind. <br>
Each functions as hitpoints(and can be damaged in combat), if any one hit 0 you are incapacitated. <br>
Each bar also functions as stamina or mana would in other games, using skills (or special attacks) reduces one or more bars just as being hit by an enemy does.<br>
Each weapon type(rifle, carbine, pistol) has special attacks that target one pool. That means its most advantageous to use the weapon that targets your opponents smallest pool (vs another fighter thats most commonly mind).<br>
NPCs can target pools as well <br>
<br>
Root cause #2 Advancement <br>
<br>
XP is awarded based on useage i.e. kill a womp rat with a pistol get 100 pistol xp, after you have enough pistol XP you can train in the pistol tree of marksman.<br>
You dont gain additional pool (effectively hitpoints) as you advance up the tree, you do gain speed and accuracy in one or more weapons and the ability to use new weapons and armor. (nowheres near as cool as it sounds)<br>
Creatures do gain additional HAM (lots of it) as well as increased skills and damage output. <br>
This resulted in what could only have been balancing nightmare for the devs, but they never did get it right its always too easy or too hard. <br>
High level creatures have area affect attacks (and can 2 shot most players). <br>
After a point in the advancement trees if you cant kill them before they reach you as a ranged combatant, you will have difficulty beating even a relatively weak opponent (again thats only *1* at a time). <br>
<br>
root cause #3 Combat flow <br>
<br>
An average fight ranged is:<br>
- spot creature at 64m (regardless of weapon) <br>
- go prone/crouched, use a warning shot to scatter multiples(they will come after you eventually) otherwise use your most damaging special attack <br>
- repeat a large damage attack until they close the distance (or if it is a range creature just repeat) <br>
- if you are prone go crouched once the creature closes the distance(cant shoot prone within a certain range).<br>
- Now you have a choice, watch the game decide the fight for you<br>
or que up your favorite attack(the one that does the most damage) and watch the game decide the fight for you. <br>
If you DONT use a specific pool targetting attack damage will randomly distribute amongst your targets 3 pools (remember to win you have to drop 1 pool to 0% dropping all 3 to 1% doesnt count).<br>
There is no move chaining ala DAOC. <br>
<br>
root cause #4 downtime <br>
<br>
In addition to the time spent awaiting normal damage to regenerate as you have in other games, SWG introduces two new types on downtime that must be taken in either a town or a camp as well as equipment wear. <br>
Wounds and &quot;battle fatigue&quot;<br>
you will gain these in addition to taking normal damage, wounds will reduce the maximum size of your pools or their regen rates until the &quot;wounds&quot; are healed by a doctor/medic (a time consuming process and one the med type has to have supplies to do) <br>
Battle fatigue makes it harder to heal you and is removed by watching or listening to entertainers back in town. <br>
<br>
root cause #5 player based economy <br>
<br>
One of the selling points of the game!<br>
But combat classes are completely dependent on others to be around when they need them or they become ineffective in combat <br>
You need:<br>
- crafters to build and repair you armor and weapons(and other things like droids and houses) <br>
- medics AND entertainers to heal your &quot;wounds&quot; <br>
And you will be seeing the &quot;healers&quot; every few hours for a considerable amount of time each visit. <br>
<br>
root cause #6 Spawn system <br>
<br>
The spawns look like what they are, randomly created relatively static NPCs with no rhyme or reason for being there, you can run for 15 minutes and see nothing then run into a valley with 4-6 camps of different mobs all waiting for you to kill them. The world doesnt look alive. <br>
--- <br>
<br>
I think I would enjoy SWG if only a few of these had been changed in beta, but sadly (for me at least) they were not. <br>
Combat to me has always looked like an afterthought, almost like the design meeting went like this: <br>
<br>
dev1: ok so we have all these professions, what do all the combat professions do again? <br>
dev2: well they leave town, 2 hours later they come back with money and wounds. They use the money to buy things from the crafters and pay the medics to heal the wounds. <br>
dev1: but what do they do while theyre outside town? <br>
<br>
dev2: I dont know well slap together some NPCs put a few <br>
different skins on them and some particle effects and let them attack the players, theyll eat it right up. We cant spend much time on this interaction, we need to get the player based economy and the crafter/merchant/medic professions up and running. <br>
<br>
dev3: thats fine but I have the entertainer profession working but outside our roleplayers noone really has a reason to ever visit them or pay them to dance for them. <br>
dev2: hmm tell you what we can put another wound type on the combat classes and let only the entertainers heal it in town. <br>
dev3: thatll work.<br>
---- <br>
<br>
I know from the devs reactions on the beta boards that this is far from the truth, but its a testament to just how bizare the way combat was implemented. <br>
<br>
The bottom line is this, so much work was put into enhancing the social and explorer motivations in this game that &quot;achievement&quot; motivation players will find little reason to play. And I'm not entirely sure that all of the social and explorers are happy with the current state of the game either (lots of &quot;too much treadmilling&quot; comments recently on the beta boards). <br>
<br>
The most depressing thing on the beta boards now is how few names I recognize from the earlier stages. Too many veteran (and very dedicated) testers simply faded over the months including many who I would call community leaders.<br>
 <br>
These were good testers with alot of patience (millions of chance cubes died in the name of crafter testing) who wrote long, detailed and rational (and often positive) posts that many others would refer to for areas of improvement or mechanics that worked in a fun manner and could serve as templates for ones in need of improvement. <br>
<br>
These people were not lost from only one area of the game but from all of them. Their losss and the lack of changes that came from their efforts colors this release. <br>
<br>
SWG is not a game for everyone, if you like to explore or socialise you might really like it. <br>
<br>
If you like having something to look forward to achieving the next day or like feeling that every day you played you actually succeeded in doing something you might not.<br>
