This doesn't surprise me in the least bit.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I cannot emphasize enough how much I wanted to like this game.  I'm even the explorer type on the MUD personality test and SWG bores and frustrates me beyond imagining!<br>
<br>
I know that you're probably all growing tired of my negative posts, but I'm simply trying to provide a counterbalance to all the positive hype (not buzz, hype) that the media is putting out for gaming sites and store promotions.  I don't want people to buy this game without being prepared for the downsides, simply because Sony is doing a censorship campaign against negative opinions.<br>
<br>
What Sony wants is a hugely successful initial launch to win over their investors, create more hype, and hence lure more people into purchasing the game.  (&quot;Hey, it sold 1 million in the first week alone?  Must be good!&quot;)<br>
<br>
Don't believe me?  Anybody know of a certain big-name cross-platform game that was recently released and has sold 2.5 million copies despite barely average gameplay and depth?  Well, if you're one of those who were suckered into buying &quot;Enter the Matrix&quot; then you're probably thinking &quot;that game shouldn't have sold 2.5 million copies... it may be ok but it isn't THAT good&quot;.<br>
<br>
I only rented it; I was quite certain it would be initially fun but not worth a full purchase.  I was right.<br>
<br>
Will some people like SWG?  Of course; it's not without some good qualities.  It's just that, by and large, most of the people who buy this game will either be online game veterans who grow disenfranchised with it quickly, or casual gamers that expect something even better than Jedi Knight II and find themselves disappointed.<br>
<br>
